SIMPLE: fiend
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: fiend
<hw>fiend</hw> <pr>(f⟦emac⟧nd)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>fend</ets>, <ets>find</ets>, <ets>fiend</ets>, <ets>feond</ets>,
fiend, foe, AS. <ets>fe⟦oacute⟧nd</ets>; akin to OS.
<ets>f⟦imac⟧ond</ets>, D. <ets>vijand</ets> enemy, OHG.
<ets>f⟦imac⟧ant</ets>, G. <ets>feind</ets>, Icel. <ets>fj⟦amac⟧nd</ets>,
Sw. & Dan. <ets>fiende</ets>, Goth. <ets>fijands</ets>; orig. p. pr. of
a verb meaning <ets>to hate</ets>, AS. <ets>fe⟦oacute⟧n</ets>,
<ets>fe⟦oacute⟧gan</ets>, OHG. <ets>f⟦imac⟧<?/n</ets>, Goth.
<ets>fijan</ets>, Skr. <ets>p⟦imac⟧y</ets> to scorn; prob. akin to E.
<ets>feud</ets> a quarrel. ⟦root⟧81. Cf. <er>Foe</er>,
<er>Friend</er>.]</ety> <def>An implacable or malicious foe; one who is
diabolically wicked or cruel; an infernal being; -- applied specifically
to the devil or a demon.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Into this wild abyss the wary <qex>fiend</qex>⟦br⟧
Stood on the brink of Hell and looked a while.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>O woman! woman! when to ill thy mind⟦br⟧
Is bent, all hell contains no fouler <qex>fiend</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Fiendful</ent>⟦br⟧
